<note xml:id="ch24n69"><p id="ch24n69pa1">The royal canal (<hi rend="italic">Nahar Malcha</hi>) might be successively restored, altered, divided, &amp;c. (Cellarius, Geograph. Antiq. tom. ii. p. 453); and these changes may serve to explain the seeming contradictions of antiquity. In the time of Julian, it must have fallen into the Euphrates [<hi rend="italic">leg.</hi> Tigris] <hi rend="italic">below</hi> Ctesiphon. [Ibn Serapion describes it as falling into the Tigris three leagues below Al-Madäin. Cp. Appendix 4.]</p></note>

